  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some extracurricular activities I could do to improve my chances at getting into Ivy League schools?",
  "response": "Getting into an Ivy League school is highly competitive, and engaging in extracurricular activities can play a significant role in strengthening your application. Here are some activities that can help set you apart:\n\n1. **Leadership Roles**: Demonstrate initiative and leadership by holding positions such as class president, starting a club, or leading a school project. Leadership experiences highlight your ability to take charge and make a difference.\n\n2. **Academic Competitions**: Participate in science fairs, math Olympiads, debate teams, or other academic contests. Excelling in these areas can showcase your intellectual curiosity and expertise.\n\n3. **Community Service**: Engage in meaningful volunteer work that reflects your passions and commitment to helping others. Starting a community initiative can also make a significant impact.\n\n4. **Arts and Performing Arts**: If you are talented in music, theater, dance, or visual arts, being active in these areas can demonstrate creativity and commitment. Consider participating in productions, exhibitions, or competitions.\n\n5. **Athletics**: Involvement in sports can display teamwork, dedication, and resilience. Achievements in athletics, such as being a team captain or winning championships, are particularly valuable.\n\n6. **Research Projects**: Conducting independent research, preferably published or presented at conferences, can demonstrate your interest and capability in pursuing scholarly work.\n\n7. **Clubs Related to Your Interests**: Engage in clubs that align with your academic interests or future career goals. For instance, if you're interested in medicine, joining a health sciences club can be beneficial.\n\n8. **Internships and Work Experience**: Gain experience in your field of interest through internships or part-time jobs. This can demonstrate maturity and readiness for real-world applications of your studies.\n\n9. **Writing and Publications**: If you have a talent for writing, consider submitting your work to publications or starting a blog. This could include journalism, creative writing, or essays.\n\n10. **Cultural or Language Clubs**: Participation in cultural activities or learning new languages can highlight your global awareness and appreciation for diversity.\n\nQuality and impact are more critical than quantity when it comes to extracurriculars. Focus on activities that genuinely interest you, where you can show continuity, depth, and significant accomplishments. Admissions committees value uniqueness and authenticity, so choose activities that reflect your true passions and aspirations.",
